data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest replacements for each assertion:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in "all match" assertion; IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "expected non-empty" vs just "expected True" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | Removed — `Single()` already throws if missing | Redundant check |

`Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is fine — MSTest has no built-in "all elements match predicate" assertion.

If the admin check should be its own assertion rather than relying on `Single()` throwing, you could also write:

```csharp
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
```

This asserts exactly one admin exists **and** returns it for further inspection.
